{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Your immune system is your body’s security team. Its job is to spot “not you” (germs, toxins, weird cells) and remove the threat—without damaging your own healthy tissues.",
      "title": "Your body’s built-in security"
    },
    {
      "text": "Defense starts at the doors: skin, mucus, tears, and stomach acid. Think of them like walls, sticky flypaper, and a moat—designed to keep most intruders out before a fight even starts.",
      "title": "Layer 1: Barriers block entry"
    },
    {
      "text": "If something gets in, your body triggers inflammation: redness, heat, swelling, pain. It’s like sounding an alarm and closing streets so helpers can rush in and contain the problem.",
      "title": "Layer 2: The alarm system"
    },
    {
      "text": "White blood cells are the main responders. Some are “patrollers” that roam, others are “station guards” in tissues. Together they constantly check IDs and react fast to danger.",
      "title": "The immune system’s main players"
    },
    {
      "text": "Innate immunity is your rapid-response team. It attacks common patterns found on many germs, so it’s quick but not picky—like spraying a fire extinguisher at the first sign of smoke.",
      "title": "Innate immunity: fast and general"
    },
    {
      "text": "Adaptive immunity is the specialist squad. It targets specific invaders with precision, but takes time to gear up—like detectives building a case before making an arrest.",
      "title": "Adaptive immunity: precise and trained"
    },
    {
      "text": "B cells make antibodies—tiny “wanted posters” that stick to germs. That tagging can block germs, clump them together, or mark them for cleanup by other immune cells.",
      "title": "Antibodies: the tagging system"
    },
    {
      "text": "T cells coordinate and fight. Helper T cells direct the response like a coach calling plays. Killer T cells destroy infected cells, like removing compromised rooms to stop a fire spreading.",
      "title": "T cells: coaches and eliminators"
    },
    {
      "text": "Lymph nodes are immune meeting hubs. They filter fluid and bring immune cells together, like a busy command center where messages, samples, and reinforcements get organized.",
      "title": "Lymph nodes: the command hubs"
    },
    {
      "text": "After a battle, memory cells remain. They’re like saved passwords: next time the same germ shows up, your response is faster and stronger, often stopping illness before you notice.",
      "title": "Immune memory: faster next time"
    },
    {
      "text": "A common confusion: inflammation and fever aren’t the enemy—they’re tools. The real goal is balance: strong enough to clear threats, controlled enough to avoid harming your own body.",
      "title": "Powerful, but needs control"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Photosynthesis is a plant’s way of “cooking” food using sunlight. It turns light energy into chemical energy stored in sugar, which the plant can use and build with.",
      "title": "Plants making food from light"
    },
    {
      "text": "Think of chloroplasts as tiny solar-powered factories inside plant cells. They capture light and run the machinery that turns simple ingredients into energy-rich molecules.",
      "title": "Chloroplasts: the solar factories"
    },
    {
      "text": "Chlorophyll is the green pigment that acts like a light-catching antenna. It absorbs mostly red and blue light and reflects green, which is why many plants look green.",
      "title": "Chlorophyll: the light catcher"
    },
    {
      "text": "In the light reactions, sunlight is converted into usable energy “batteries” called ATP and NADPH. It’s like charging power packs before you start building anything.",
      "title": "Light reactions: charging energy"
    },
    {
      "text": "During these light reactions, water is split apart. Oxygen gas is released as a byproduct—like exhaust from a process—while the remaining parts help power the next steps.",
      "title": "Water splitting and oxygen"
    },
    {
      "text": "Carbon fixation is where carbon dioxide (CO₂) gets turned into carbon-based molecules. Imagine grabbing loose LEGO bricks from the air and snapping them into a starter piece.",
      "title": "Carbon fixation: grabbing CO₂"
    },
    {
      "text": "The Calvin cycle uses ATP and NADPH to build sugars from fixed carbon. Like using charged power packs to assemble a sturdy structure, step by step, until you get a usable product.",
      "title": "Calvin cycle: building sugar"
    },
    {
      "text": "Key idea: light reactions need light directly, but the Calvin cycle mostly needs the energy made by light reactions. So “light” and “sugar-building” are connected like charging and spending.",
      "title": "How the two stages team up"
    },
    {
      "text": "You can spot photosynthesis by its inputs and outputs: it uses CO₂ and water plus light, and it makes sugars and releases oxygen. It’s a trade—ingredients in, products out.",
      "title": "Inputs and outputs to remember"
    },
    {
      "text": "Common mix-up: plants don’t “make energy” from nothing—they transform it. The energy ends up stored in sugar’s chemical bonds, like money moved into a savings account.",
      "title": "A common confusion clarified"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "CRISPR-Cas9 is like a GPS-guided pair of scissors for DNA. You choose a target “address” in the genome, and the system goes there, cuts, and lets the cell patch the cut—sometimes with changes.",
      "title": "CRISPR in one picture"
    },
    {
      "text": "It’s mainly three parts: a guide RNA (the address label), the Cas9 protein (the scissors), and the cell’s own DNA repair crew (the builders who fix the cut).",
      "title": "The three main players"
    },
    {
      "text": "Guide RNA is a short RNA that matches the DNA sequence you want to edit. Think of it like a search bar query: it’s designed to “spell-check” the genome until it finds a close match.",
      "title": "Guide RNA: the targeting system"
    },
    {
      "text": "Cas9 is a protein that grabs the guide RNA and uses it as a map. Like a trained dog following a scent, Cas9 doesn’t decide where to go—the guide RNA steers it.",
      "title": "Cas9: the programmable scissors"
    },
    {
      "text": "Cas9 won’t cut just anywhere. It looks for a tiny nearby “flag” in the DNA called a PAM. Imagine a door keycard reader: no PAM, no entry—so it adds a safety checkpoint.",
      "title": "PAM: the required checkpoint"
    },
    {
      "text": "Once the guide RNA pairs with the matching DNA, Cas9 makes a double-strand break—both DNA strands snap. It’s like cutting a rope clean through, not just nicking one fiber.",
      "title": "The cut: a double-strand break"
    },
    {
      "text": "After the cut, the cell rushes to fix it. CRISPR doesn’t “write” edits by itself—it creates a break, and the cell’s repair systems do the real rewriting during the patch job.",
      "title": "Cells do the editing via repair"
    },
    {
      "text": "One repair path, NHEJ, is quick and messy—like taping a torn page fast. It often adds or removes a few DNA letters (indels), which can disrupt a gene and effectively turn it off.",
      "title": "Repair option 1: NHEJ (messy fix)"
    },
    {
      "text": "Another path, HDR, is like fixing the page using a clean template. If a DNA template is available, the cell can copy from it, allowing precise swaps, insertions, or corrections.",
      "title": "Repair option 2: HDR (template fix)"
    },
    {
      "text": "A common confusion: CRISPR isn’t “gene pasting” by default. It’s more like making a cut at a chosen spot—what you get depends on which repair route the cell uses afterward.",
      "title": "What CRISPR is (and isn’t)"
    },
    {
      "text": "You can recognize CRISPR thinking when you hear: target sequence + guide RNA + PAM + cut + repair outcome. Those five ideas are the core mental map for how CRISPR edits DNA.",
      "title": "The core map to remember"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Neurotransmissão é a “conversa” entre neurônios. Parte da mensagem viaja como eletricidade dentro do neurônio e, ao chegar no final, vira um sinal químico para alcançar o próximo neurônio.",
      "title": "A conversa dos neurônios"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pense no neurônio como um cabo vivo: ele recebe sinais nos dendritos, integra tudo no corpo celular e envia a decisão pelo axônio, como um fio levando a informação até o destino.",
      "title": "O neurônio como um cabo vivo"
    },
    {
      "text": "O potencial de ação é o “clique” do neurônio: um pulso elétrico curto e forte que corre pelo axônio sem perder força, como uma ola que se propaga por um estádio.",
      "title": "O pulso elétrico (potencial de ação)"
    },
    {
      "text": "No fim do axônio fica o terminal, o “ponto de entrega”. Quando o pulso chega, ele avisa: é hora de enviar a mensagem para fora, rumo ao próximo neurônio.",
      "title": "Chegando ao terminal do axônio"
    },
    {
      "text": "A sinapse é a pequena fresta entre células, como o espaço entre dois carros numa balsa. Eles não encostam: a informação precisa cruzar esse vão por outro meio.",
      "title": "Sinapse: a fresta entre neurônios"
    },
    {
      "text": "Neurotransmissores são os “mensageiros químicos”. Eles ficam guardados em vesículas, como encomendas em caixas, esperando o sinal para serem liberados.",
      "title": "Neurotransmissores: os mensageiros"
    },
    {
      "text": "Quando o pulso chega, canais de cálcio se abrem e isso dispara a fusão das vesículas com a membrana. Imagine apertar um botão que faz as caixas se abrirem na borda.",
      "title": "Cálcio: o gatilho da liberação"
    },
    {
      "text": "Os neurotransmissores atravessam a fenda sináptica e se ligam a receptores no neurônio seguinte, como chave e fechadura. Só a “chave” certa abre aquela porta.",
      "title": "Receptores: as fechaduras certas"
    },
    {
      "text": "Alguns receptores abrem canais e mudam a voltagem rápido; outros acionam efeitos mais lentos, como ajustar configurações. É tipo tocar uma nota vs. mexer no equalizador.",
      "title": "Dois jeitos de agir: rápido e lento"
    },
    {
      "text": "A mensagem pode excitar (aproximar do disparo) ou inibir (afastar do disparo). Pense em acelerador e freio: o neurônio decide somando muitos empurrões e puxões.",
      "title": "Excitação e inibição"
    },
    {
      "text": "O neurônio não responde a um único recado: ele integra vários sinais ao mesmo tempo, como uma votação. Só quando a soma passa um limiar ele dispara o próximo pulso.",
      "title": "Somando sinais: o “voto” neuronal"
    },
    {
      "text": "Para a conversa não virar eco, o neurotransmissor precisa ser removido: pode ser recaptado, degradado ou se difundir. É como limpar a tinta depois de escrever um bilhete.",
      "title": "Encerrando o sinal: limpeza sináptica"
    },
    {
      "text": "Você reconhece a neurotransmissão em coisas do dia a dia: reflexos rápidos, humor, atenção, sono e movimento. Tudo isso depende de redes de sinapses conversando sem parar.",
      "title": "Onde isso aparece na vida real"
    },
    {
      "text": "Confusão comum: achar que é só elétrico ou só químico. Dentro do neurônio, o sinal é principalmente elétrico; entre neurônios, a ponte costuma ser química (a sinapse).",
      "title": "Um mal-entendido bem comum"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Un mecanismo de consenso es el “acuerdo de grupo” que usa una blockchain para decidir qué bloque es el válido. Piensa en un marcador de partido: todos ven el juego, pero necesitan una forma única de fijar el resultado oficial.",
      "title": "Qué es consenso en blockchain"
    },
    {
      "text": "Cada bloque es como una página nueva del libro contable: incluye transacciones y un “enlace” al bloque anterior. Ese enlace hace que, si cambias una página vieja, se note en todas las siguientes.",
      "title": "Qué se está poniendo de acuerdo"
    },
    {
      "text": "Las transacciones primero se anuncian a la red y quedan “en espera”. Los nodos las revisan con reglas claras (firmas válidas, no gastar dos veces, formato). Como un portero: deja pasar solo entradas auténticas.",
      "title": "Transacciones: de mensaje a candidata"
    },
    {
      "text": "Validar transacciones no es lo mismo que elegir el siguiente bloque. Muchas pueden ser correctas, pero el consenso decide cuál conjunto entra primero al libro y en qué orden, para que todos terminen con la misma historia.",
      "title": "Validar vs. ordenar: dos tareas"
    },
    {
      "text": "Un bloque necesita una prueba que lo haga costoso de falsificar y fácil de comprobar. Es como un sello de seguridad: difícil de fabricar, rápido de verificar con una mirada.",
      "title": "La “prueba” que convence a todos"
    },
    {
      "text": "En Proof of Work, los mineros compiten resolviendo un rompecabezas: encontrar un número que haga que el bloque cumpla una condición. Es como tirar dados hasta que salga una combinación exacta.",
      "title": "Proof of Work (PoW) en simple"
    },
    {
      "text": "Cuando alguien encuentra la solución, la publica con el bloque. Los demás no repiten todo el esfuerzo: solo verifican que la solución encaja. Como revisar una cuenta: es más rápido comprobar que hacerla desde cero.",
      "title": "Verificación rápida del trabajo"
    },
    {
      "text": "Si dos bloques aparecen a la vez, la red sigue la cadena con más trabajo acumulado (la más “pesada”). Imagínalo como elegir la fila más larga de tickets sellados: cuesta más falsificarla que a una corta.",
      "title": "Qué pasa si hay dos versiones"
    },
    {
      "text": "Las confirmaciones son capas extra de seguridad: mientras más bloques se apilan encima, más caro sería reescribir el pasado. Como poner más candados en una puerta: cada uno añade fricción al atacante.",
      "title": "Por qué esperar confirmaciones"
    },
    {
      "text": "El consenso se apoya en incentivos: quien propone bloques válidos gana recompensa y comisiones; quien intenta engañar suele perder tiempo y dinero. Es como un juego con reglas donde hacer trampa sale caro.",
      "title": "Incentivos: reglas + recompensas"
    },
    {
      "text": "Error típico: creer que PoW “validó” una transacción solo por incluirla. En realidad: reglas + firmas la hacen válida; PoW ayuda a que todos acepten la misma versión del orden y dificulta cambiarla después.",
      "title": "Confusión común: PoW no es magia"
    },
    {
      "text": "Entender consenso te deja ver por qué una blockchain puede operar sin jefe: combina reglas verificables, una forma de elegir el siguiente bloque y un criterio para resolver empates, hasta que la red converge.",
      "title": "La idea clave que une todo"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "A compiler is like a translator and a factory in one: it takes code you write and produces a new “product” (machine code) that the CPU can run directly.",
      "title": "Compiler = translator + factory"
    },
    {
      "text": "Most compilers don’t jump straight to machine code. They move through stages, like a cooking line: prep, taste, adjust, and only then plate the final dish.",
      "title": "It works in phases"
    },
    {
      "text": "First is lexing: turning raw text into tokens. Think of scanning a sentence and labeling pieces like WORD, NUMBER, “;”. It’s breaking letters into meaningful chunks.",
      "title": "From text to tokens (lexing)"
    },
    {
      "text": "Next is parsing: tokens become a structured tree (an AST). Like diagramming a sentence so you know what attaches to what—so “2 + 3 * 4” has the right shape.",
      "title": "Building a syntax tree (parsing)"
    },
    {
      "text": "Semantic analysis checks meaning: are variables declared, types compatible, names in scope? Like making sure a recipe says “2 cups flour,” not “2 cups bicycle.”",
      "title": "Checking meaning (semantics)"
    },
    {
      "text": "Many compilers translate the AST into an intermediate representation (IR). Think of IR as a universal blueprint—easier to optimize and easier to target many different CPUs.",
      "title": "A middle language (IR)"
    },
    {
      "text": "Optimization reshapes the IR to run faster or smaller without changing results. Like rearranging errands to avoid backtracking—same stops, less wasted travel.",
      "title": "Making it efficient (optimization)"
    },
    {
      "text": "Code generation turns IR into target instructions (plus register choices, calling conventions). It’s like assigning chefs to stations and deciding which tools fit in your kitchen.",
      "title": "Producing machine instructions"
    },
    {
      "text": "Finally, assembly/linking/package steps may combine your code with libraries and resolve names/addresses. Like stitching chapters into one book and adding a table of contents.",
      "title": "Putting it all together"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "A neural net “learns” by adjusting its connection strengths (weights) so its outputs get closer to the right answers. Think of it like tuning a huge mixing board: tiny knob turns, better sound over time.",
      "title": "Learning = tuning the weights"
    },
    {
      "text": "In a forward pass, data flows layer by layer to produce a prediction. Like ingredients moving down an assembly line, each layer transforms the input a bit until you get the final product: the output.",
      "title": "Forward pass: make a prediction"
    },
    {
      "text": "The loss is a single number that says how wrong the prediction was. Imagine darts: the board is the target, and loss is the distance from the bullseye—smaller means closer to what you wanted.",
      "title": "Loss: measuring the mistake"
    },
    {
      "text": "Backpropagation figures out how each weight affected the loss by sending a signal backward through the network. Like replaying a play in slow motion to see which moves led to the missed shot.",
      "title": "Backprop: trace error backward"
    },
    {
      "text": "Gradients are the “slope” of the loss with respect to each weight: which direction increases or decreases error, and by how much. Like feeling the steepness of a hill to know the fastest way down.",
      "title": "Gradients: direction and strength"
    },
    {
      "text": "With gradient descent, you update weights opposite the gradient to reduce loss. It’s like adjusting a recipe: if it’s too salty, you don’t add more salt—you nudge ingredients the other way.",
      "title": "Weight updates: small corrective nudges"
    },
    {
      "text": "The learning rate controls step size. Too big is like over-steering and swerving past your lane; too small is inching along. The goal is steady progress without bouncing around.",
      "title": "Learning rate: step size control"
    },
    {
      "text": "One pass through many examples makes an epoch. Training repeats epochs so the network improves gradually, like practicing a song: each run-through fixes a few more rough notes.",
      "title": "Epochs: practice in loops"
    },
    {
      "text": "It rarely updates using all data at once. Mini-batches are small chunks that give noisy-but-fast gradients—like taste-testing soup with a spoonful instead of drinking the whole pot each time.",
      "title": "Mini-batches: quick feedback"
    },
    {
      "text": "A common confusion: backprop doesn’t “send answers backward.” It sends information about sensitivity—how much each weight change would affect the loss—so the network knows what to tweak.",
      "title": "What backprop really sends"
    },
    {
      "text": "When this clicks, training stops feeling magical: it’s just prediction → score the error → compute sensitivities → adjust. Like a coach reviewing plays, scoring mistakes, then refining drills.",
      "title": "The full loop in one sentence"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Política monetária é o “controle do termostato” da economia. O banco central ajusta condições financeiras para esfriar quando há excesso de inflação e aquecer quando a atividade está fraca.",
      "title": "O termostato da economia"
    },
    {
      "text": "O objetivo mais famoso é manter preços sob controle (inflação). Em muitos países também conta emprego e estabilidade do sistema financeiro. É como equilibrar uma bicicleta: correções pequenas evitam tombos grandes.",
      "title": "O que ela tenta equilibrar"
    },
    {
      "text": "A taxa de juros básica é o preço do dinheiro no curto prazo. Ela serve como referência: quando muda, influencia várias outras taxas na economia, como se fosse a “nota” que puxa a banda toda.",
      "title": "A ferramenta principal: juros"
    },
    {
      "text": "Quando a taxa sobe, empréstimos tendem a ficar mais caros e poupar fica mais atraente. Quando cai, financiar e investir costuma ficar mais fácil. Pense num freio e um acelerador — mas com atraso na resposta.",
      "title": "Como juros mudam decisões"
    },
    {
      "text": "Transmissão é o caminho da decisão do banco central até seu bolso. Vai dos juros de curto prazo para bancos, crédito, consumo, investimento, câmbio e, por fim, preços e empregos — como uma fileira de dominós.",
      "title": "O “mecanismo de transmissão”"
    },
    {
      "text": "Canal do crédito: com juros e condições mais apertados, bancos emprestam menos ou cobram mais. Com condições mais soltas, o crédito circula. É como abrir ou fechar a torneira que alimenta compras parceladas e investimentos.",
      "title": "Canal do crédito"
    },
    {
      "text": "Canal das expectativas: se pessoas e empresas acreditam que a inflação vai cair, reajustam preços e salários com menos pressa. É tipo um boato no estádio: muda o comportamento antes mesmo do jogo acabar.",
      "title": "Canal das expectativas"
    },
    {
      "text": "Canal do câmbio: juros mais altos podem atrair capital e fortalecer a moeda; mais baixos podem enfraquecê-la. Moeda forte barateia importados; fraca encarece. Imagine um “desconto” ou “acréscimo” nos preços vindos de fora.",
      "title": "Canal do câmbio"
    },
    {
      "text": "Além dos juros, há operações de mercado aberto (compra/venda de títulos) para ajustar liquidez. É como o banco central “dosar combustível” no sistema bancário para manter as taxas perto da meta.",
      "title": "Liquidez e títulos no mercado"
    },
    {
      "text": "Em crises, pode usar medidas não convencionais: comprar muitos ativos, dar crédito direto a mercados ou orientar expectativas. Pense em ferramentas extras na caixa quando o volante (juros) já está no limite.",
      "title": "Ferramentas fora do comum"
    },
    {
      "text": "Um ponto-chave: política monetária não age na hora. Leva meses para afetar demanda e inflação, como mexer no forno: a temperatura muda agora, mas o bolo demora a assar.",
      "title": "Os efeitos têm atraso"
    },
    {
      "text": "Confusão comum: “juros altos = sempre ruim” ou “sempre bom”. Depende do problema. Se a inflação está alta, juros podem ser o remédio amargo. Se a economia está fraca, cortar juros pode ajudar a respirar.",
      "title": "O que muita gente confunde"
    },
    {
      "text": "Entender o “como funciona” ajuda a ler notícias e decisões: quando o banco central fala em meta, crédito, expectativas e câmbio, ele está descrevendo quais dominós quer derrubar — e em que direção.",
      "title": "Por que isso importa"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "A vaccine is like a “wanted poster” for your immune system. It safely shows your body what a specific germ looks like, so you can react fast if the real thing ever shows up.",
      "title": "Vaccines = immune training"
    },
    {
      "text": "Your immune system has scouts (that spot threats), messengers (that call for help), and fighters (that attack). Vaccines mainly help the system practice recognizing one exact target.",
      "title": "Meet the immune team"
    },
    {
      "text": "The key target is called an antigen—think of it as the germ’s uniform or logo. Vaccines present antigens (or instructions to make them) so your immune system learns the look.",
      "title": "The “logo” your body learns"
    },
    {
      "text": "After vaccination, your body makes antibodies—tiny “lock picks” designed to stick to that antigen. When antibodies bind, they can block infection and flag the germ for cleanup.",
      "title": "Antibodies: custom-fit defenders"
    },
    {
      "text": "Vaccines also create memory B cells and T cells. They’re like saved game progress: if you’re exposed later, you don’t start from zero—you reload a strong, faster response.",
      "title": "Immune memory is the real prize"
    },
    {
      "text": "That practice response can cause soreness, fever, or fatigue. It’s like muscle aches after a workout—signs your immune system is training, not the disease taking over.",
      "title": "Why side effects happen"
    },
    {
      "text": "Live attenuated vaccines use a weakened germ—like sparring with a softer opponent. They often build strong memory but aren’t suitable for everyone.",
      "title": "Live weakened vaccines"
    },
    {
      "text": "Inactivated vaccines use a killed germ—more like practicing with a dummy. They can be very safe but may need boosters to keep your skills sharp.",
      "title": "Inactivated (killed) vaccines"
    },
    {
      "text": "Subunit and conjugate vaccines use only key pieces of the germ. Imagine learning a face from a clear photo instead of meeting the whole person—focused and targeted.",
      "title": "Subunit & conjugate vaccines"
    },
    {
      "text": "mRNA and viral-vector vaccines deliver instructions so your cells briefly make a harmless antigen. It’s like a temporary recipe card—your body cooks the “sample,” then tosses the card.",
      "title": "mRNA & vector vaccines"
    },
    {
      "text": "Immunity builds over time. Your first dose is the lesson; later doses can be like review sessions that raise antibody levels and strengthen memory cells.",
      "title": "How protection develops"
    },
    {
      "text": "A common mix-up: vaccines don’t usually create an instant force field, and protection can fade. The goal is a faster, stronger response that prevents severe illness and spread.",
      "title": "Common misunderstandings"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
